  "tacticalAnalysis": {
    "IRQ": {
      "summary": "Iraq's 4-4-2 set up to frustrate Norway but were overwhelmed by the quality gap. Deep defensive blocks (mid and low block for 50% of out-of-possession time) absorbed early pressure but HAALAND's movement found pockets to exploit. The lone moment of quality came via HUSSEIN's headed goal from a cross at 39'. Iraq's high pressing volume (288 pressures) was more reactive than proactive, with recovery time of 22.84s exposing defensive disorganisation after turnovers.",
      "strengths": [
        "HUSSEIN's aerial ability and constant runs in-behind (59 offers made) created the opening for Iraq's goal and caused problems for Norway's centre-backs",
        "MERCHAS DOSKI's work rate on the left side — 15 direct pressures and 9 possession regains — provided Iraq's best defensive output",
        "Compact 4-4-2 block in mid-third limited Norway's clear chances in the first half — 2-1 at half-time showed defensive resilience",
        "High volume of pressing (288 total pressures) created some turnovers but timing and positioning could have been better exploited"
      ],
      "weaknesses": [
        "Only 1.2 xG despite 11 attempts — poor shot quality and decision-making in the final third let Norway off the hook repeatedly",
        "34.7% possession was unsustainable — Norway dictated tempo completely and Iraq could not build sustained attacks",
        "Defensively vulnerable from corners and set pieces — OSTIGARD's 76' header highlighted a lack of aerial organisation at corners",
        "After HAALAND's 43' goal, Iraq showed no tactical response — the team failed to adapt formation or pressing structure after going 3-1 down"
      ]
    },
    "NOR": {
      "summary": "Norway were utterly dominant against Iraq, controlling possession (57.2%), territory, and chances throughout. The 4-1-2-3 with BERGE as a controlling pivot and HAALAND spearheading a fluid attacking front three proved devastating. HAALAND's 2 goals and OSTIGARD's set-piece header from the bench sealed an emphatic win. Norway's build-up was patient and measured, with HEGGEM and RYERSON providing width while ODEGAARD and BERGE combined in midfield.",
      "strengths": [
        "HAALAND was unplayable — 2 goals, 4 shots on target, 36.5 km/h top speed. His movement between lines and finishing quality decided the match",
        "BERGE's 80 passes at 98% completion with 15 completed line breaks showed complete midfield control — Iraq could not press him effectively",
        "Set-piece threat was outstanding — OSTIGARD's headed goal from a corner showed Norway's training in dead-ball situations",
        "Flexible attacking structure with SORLOTH, NUSA, and HAALAND interchanging created multiple angles of attack that Iraq's 4-4-2 could not handle"
      ],
      "weaknesses": [
        "Despite dominance, xG was 2.41 for 4 goals — slightly fortunate finishing, with Norway conceding a goal from a cross at 39' when defensive shape was loose",
        "Only 3 completed crosses from 11 attempted — crossing accuracy was poor and most attacks relied on intricate passing combinations instead",
        "Norway's low pressing volume (173 pressures) means they rely on possession to defend — against a counter-attacking team they could be exposed",
        "First half nearly undone by a direct ball and Iraq cross at 39' — showed that simple diagonal delivery can bypass Norway's press"
      ]
    }
